mt_raw:
With the assistance of the Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, the Financial Secretary is responsible for policies to maintain the stability and soundness of Hong Kong’s financial system and to consolidate Hong Kong’s status as an international financial centre. To implement these policies, the duties of the Monetary Authority include:
- Promoting the overall stability and effective operation of the banking system;
- Cooperating with other relevant institutions and organizations to develop the debt market;
- Handling matters relating to the issuance and circulation of legal tender notes and coins;
- Promoting the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure by developing payment, clearing, and settlement systems, and, where appropriate, operating such systems; and
- Cooperating with other relevant institutions and organizations to foster confidence in Hong Kong’s currency and financial system, and implementing appropriate market development measures to help enhance the international competitiveness of Hong Kong’s financial services.

The monetary base (Table 1) includes:
- Certificates of Indebtedness (providing full backing for banknotes issued by the three note-issuing banks);
- Government-issued currency notes and coins;
- The Aggregate Balance of settlement accounts maintained with the HKMA; and
- Exchange Fund Bills and Notes issued by the HKMA on behalf of the government.

The HKMA Fintech Facilitation Office continued to collaborate with various banking sectors to implement the "Fintech 2025" strategy, promoting the widespread adoption of fintech within the industry and enhancing Hong Kong’s position as a fintech hub in Asia. Major initiatives launched during the year included:
- Promoting the application of Regtech and conducting fintech adoption assessments;
- Advancing wholesale central bank digital currency (CBDC) initiatives to improve cross-border payments;
- Deepening research on the issuance of retail CBDC in Hong Kong (i.e., the "e-HKD");
- Launching the Commercial Data Interchange;
- Strengthening talent development;
- Leveraging policy resources to support the fintech ecosystem;
- Enhancing cross-border fintech cooperation; and
- Promoting broader use of the Faster Payment System (FPS).

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has set the following investment objectives for the EF:
(i) Capital preservation;
(ii) Ensuring that the entire monetary base is at all times fully backed by highly liquid US dollar assets;
(iii) Ensuring sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(iv) Subject to (i) to (iii) above, seeking to maximize investment returns to preserve the long-term purchasing power of the EF.

The terms of reference of the Risk Committee are as follows:
- To identify potential risks and threats faced by the HKMA and formulate strategies to mitigate their impact;
- To review the existing risk management systems of various departments, identify possible loopholes and significant risks, and ensure that appropriate measures are in place to address such situations;
- To standardize risk assessment criteria and methodologies, and to determine resource management priorities for the identified risks; and
- To encourage and strengthen the internal risk management culture within the HKMA, promoting appropriate delegation and monitoring.

The audit procedures for the valuation of financial assets and financial liabilities measured at fair value included:
- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and financial liabilities, including relevant monitoring controls;
- Evaluating and testing the monitoring controls, including relevant application controls of the computer systems;
- Obtaining confirmations regarding the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and financial liabilities;
- For market-quoted prices, verifying prices against independent sources;
- For valuation techniques using inputs based on observable market data, evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the assumptions, and verifying the inputs against independent sources; and
- For valuation techniques using significant unobservable inputs, evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the related assumptions and inputs.

In conducting an audit in accordance with the Audit Commission auditing standards, I exercise professional judgement and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audit. I also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks; and obtain audit evidence that is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for my opinion. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal controls;
- Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audit in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal control;
- Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of accounting estimates and related disclosures made by the Monetary Authority;
- Conclude on the appropriateness of the Monetary Authority’s use of the going concern basis of accounting and, based on the audit evidence obtained, whether a material uncertainty exists related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that a material uncertainty exists, I am required to draw attention in my auditor’s report to the related disclosures in the financial statements or, if such disclosures are inadequate, to issue a modified opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. However, future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure and content of the financial statements, including the disclosures, and whether the financial statements represent the underlying transactions and events in a manner that achieves fair presentation; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for the direction, supervision and performance of the Group audit. I remain solely responsible for my audit opinion.
